SIMPLE: invective
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invective
<hw>In*vec"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>invectivus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>invectif</ets>. See
<er>Inveigh</er>.]</ety> <def>Characterized by invection; critical;
denunciatory; satirical; abusive; railing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invective</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Invective
<hw>In*vec"tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>invective</ets>.]</ety> <def>An expression which inveighs or rails
against a person; a severe or violent censure or reproach; something
uttered or written, intended to cast opprobrium, censure, or reproach on
another; a harsh or reproachful accusation; -- followed by
<ptcl>against</ptcl>, having reference to the person or thing affected;
<as>as, an <ex>invective</ex> against tyranny</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The world will be able to judge of his [Junius'] motives for
writing such famous <qex>invectives</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Draper.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Abuse; censure; reproach; satire; sarcasm;
railing; diatribe. See <er>Abuse</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invectively</ent>⟦br⟧
